Tecumseh Communications was chartered to pursue early-adopter status in Southern Oregon and Northern California on the Starlink Network now under construction by SpaceX.
That's right, we think billionaire-mad-scientist Elon Musk is going to deliver, and the Starlink Network is going to bring a lot of new possibilities, especially to the people of our region. But it is a new technology that, to date, has seen very little use outside the U.S. military. That presents some challenges.
The first thing we need is support from those who can help with the conversation that needs to be had with SpaceX; because maybe SpaceX can build and manage the space side of the network on its own, but the terran side is going to be built and maintained by outfits like oursâ€”lots of them, most likely.
Right now, we need people with backgrounds in engineering, science, military communications, computer programming, digital networking and electrical construction to help steer the conversation we need to be having with the people who are launching the satellites and building the antennas. We'll help them to build and test the tools, equipment and procedures that will be neeeded to install, maintain and service the network's ground-bases as it comes online.
If we do our job right, we should bring a lot of competitive skills and training to the people in this region, and that means jobs, good jobs that pay well.
Can you give us a hand?
Sincerely,
Kein Pope Chief Executive Tecumseh Communications
